Date:    Fri, 01 Oct 93 18:26:37 -0400
From:    trimm@netcom.com (Trimm Industries)
Subject: Re: Viruses and RAID 5 technolgy

KIDAJ.TRANSCOM@transcom.safb.af.mil (KIDA JOHN H) writes:
>Has anyone worked out a sound method of removing viruses from
>RAID 5 arrays?
>
>I am developing a SOP manual and the question came up.

As a vendor of RAID-Ready Disk Enclosures, we get questions like this
all the time.  The simple fact is, that RAID technology subsystems
behave differently than regular disk with respect to viruses in only
one way - the virus can infect the array even if one drive in a rank
is down!  In that sense, you have a "Highly Available, Fault Tolerant
Virus (tm)".

The fault tolerance in a RAID array only protects you from hardware
failure; software errors that corrupt data, whether on purpose or
by accident, still corrupt the same way.  Thus, buying RAID does not
impact one way or the other on the virus issue.

Exception: if you have a software based RAID system, such as CorelRAID,
Integra, Chantal or whatever, some viruses may behave in strange and
unpredictable ways, much as if the infection was taking place on a
Stacker partition.

