Date:    Thu, 30 Sep 93 15:27:23 -0400
From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: Satan Bug Virus (PC)

Apparently some yo-yo was running around D.C. panicing people about the
Satan Bug (SBUG or Sat-Bug) virus. The name comes from a non-displayed
ASCII string in the Virus.

Having taken a quick look at the thingie, can make some comments.

1) Virus is very obvious in memory - takes over 9k from the top of
   memory (see the FAQ) and causes a BIOS/DOS memory mismatch. My
   CHKMEM (FreeWare in FixUtil5) will flag immediately without knowing
   anything about the PC.

2) The worst aspect is the complex polymorphic encryption used. While it
   is very easy to spot (files grow by 3-5k and no "stealth" is used) it
   is rather difficult to remove since the oringinal size is lost and the
   real opening bytes are now encrypted).

3) It is a "fast infector" - will infect any .EXE or .COM appearing file
   opened so finding one or two no-executable files flagged as infected
   without any .COM or .EXE and 640k of memory available would warrant
   a "second opinion". F-Prot v209d and SCAN v108 both will detect the
   infection.

4) Protection can be had simply by specifying the COMSPEC in lower case.
   The virus will not become resident/spread unless certain elaberate
   (but typical DOS default) criteria are met.

5) The virus specifically tries to remove the validation code appended
   to executables by certain anti-viral products (IMHO not a good idea
   anyway).

					Hope this helps,

						Padgett

