Date:    Fri, 01 Oct 93 06:23:48 -0000
From:    cctr132@cantva.canterbury.ac.nz (Nick FitzGerald, PC Software Consulta
	  nt, CSC, UoC, NZ)
Subject: Re: boot viruses, without booting from an infected disk (PC)

nathan@remus.rutgers.edu (Nathaniel Schiffman) writes:

>>James W. Kaiser, <james.w.kaiser.1@nd.edu>, reports:
>>>
>>> I have a friend who got infected by a boot sector virus and claims the
>>> machine was _never_ booted with the infected floppy in the machine. I don't
>>> see how this is possible. I suspect it actually happened but he just doesn'
t
>>> remember it. Is it possible?

You should read the Virus-L/comp.virus FAQ.  The basics needed to answer
your question are all there--below I add some of my opinion as well. 8-)

No, it's not possible!  Well, it is really, with what are sometimes
referred to as "droppers" (they are really a type of trojan program,
purporting to do one thing and/or installing a virus in a "non-standard"
way).  Such beasties are rare (to non-existent--comments anyone?).

If a user has a boot infector and they tell you their machine --never--
is booted from a floppy they are lying (with a high enough likelihood
for me).  One reason this is common is because when they -do- boot from
a floppy, they get the message

Non-System disk or disk error
Replace and strike any key when ready

because they are normally doing so from a non-bootable one, then they
open the drive door and let the boot continue from the hard disk.  To
most users this is seen/reported as booting from the hard disk!

> I've seen cases where someone is using WordPefect, and they load in a file of
f
> an infected disk (or save a file to the disk) and the hard drive that
> WordPerfect is on gets infected with the virus. Scary, eh? We used Vshield to
> stop that.

I'd have hoped that comp.virus/virus-l was above this sort of drivel!!

Nathaniel would do himself a favour by reading the FAQ carefully!!!!

The process described above --cannot-- result in an infected hard disk,
full stop, period, NEVER.

Well, in theory it -could-, though I am -not- suggesting that there is
actually an implementation of something like the following.  A resident
program loaded before WP (or any other app) ran could hook various disk
functions and when it sees a floppy disk access (caused by WP looking
for/loading a file) it could check the diskette to see if Stoned (or
some other boot virus) was present, and if so, it could do a non-
standard virus installation to the hard disk.

Why someone would -bother- doing this is completely beyond me.

What Nathaniel -may- have seen, and mis-reported, is the well-known
effect where, under certain conditions, access of an infected floppy
causes the boot sector to be re-read and the infected boot code -can-
remain in memory (in a disk buffer) long enough after the process that
read it terminates, that it is picked up by the --memory scan-- of some/
most scanners.  This is sometimes referred to as "ghosting".  NOTE that
in such cases the virus code is --not active-- (-despite- the wording of
the warning messages certain popular scanners pop-up in these cases), as
it has not been --executed-- in any sense, so hasn't had a chance to
hook into the usual system function calls it uses to do its work.

