Min-Chin Hsiao (minchin@widget.seas.upenn.edu) writes:

> 	I thought I could trust Central Point Anti-Virus

Big mistake. CPAV/MSAV/TNTVIRUS is one of the worst of the popular
anti-virus programs around...

> but it did let me down very badly....

Nothing surprising...

> 	My hard disk was infected by V-Sign virus after lending to a
> friend.  This virus, I think, creats a copy of it's own BOOT.CPS which
> Bootsafe in CPAV uses to check against hard disk boot sector and

No, the V-Sign virus doesn't do anything like this. Either CPAV has
messed something, or you have told you to update the information after
it has detected that the boot sector has changed.

> Bootsafe.  I am not sure if this virus is CPAV specific but judging
> from the way it behaves, it seems like it is.

Nope, it isn't.

> CPAV failed to recognize anything wrong with MBR and partition table.

Hm, in theory, BOOTSAFE should have detected the change in the MBR and
should have restored it automatically...

> The TSR, VSafe did not prevent MBR from being overwritten.

Of course. The virus infects the MBR when you try to boot from an
infected floppy (i.e., and infected floppy forgotten in drive A: when
you turn your computer on). At this time VSAFE is not loaded yet
(actually, even the operating system is not loaded yet), so there is
nothing strange that it has not detected the act of modifying your MBR
by the virus.

> 	To my disappointment, CPAV that comes with PCTOOLS v8 and For
> windows could not recognized this virus after scanning through it's
> database.

That's really a pity, because V-Sign is a relatively widespread
virus. But, the detection rate of CPAV 1.4 is rather miserable -
something like 68% and even that only if you have installed the latest
scan strings update.

> It also kind of surprise me that this virus is specifically
